    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-09T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-09T17:00:00-05:00" n="250"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d250">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">548.D1/141: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-09T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 9, 1934—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>87. You may in your discretion join with the British Ambassador Berlin,<note
                        n="11" xml:id="d250fn11">Sir Eric Clare Edmund Phipps.</note> who it is
                    understood has received similar instructions, in supporting proposal of James G.
                    McDonald that he be enabled to negotiate with an authorized representative of
                    the Reich concerning transfer of moneys involving (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)
                    income for living expenditures of refugees, and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) some
                    capital for purposes of establishment, as well as the question of insurance and
                    pensions owing to former Government functionaries, including professors. If the
                    Germans take the position that this is entirely a domestic matter, you may point
                    out that German citizens are becoming in one way or another public charges on
                    foreign countries. We leave to you and Phipps the decision as to the best time
                    and manner of approaching the German authorities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
